comments:
There's an easy workaround: Just wrap the TextField in a Semantics widget with `explicitChildNodes: true`.

```dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';

void main() => runApp(MyApp());

class MyApp extends StatelessWidget {
  // This widget is the root of your application.
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return MaterialApp(
      title: 'Flutter Demo',
      theme: ThemeData(
        primarySwatch: Colors.blue,
      ),
      home: Foo(title: 'Flutter Demo Home Page'),
    );
  }
}

class Foo extends StatelessWidget {
  Foo({this.title});

  final String title;

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      appBar: AppBar(
        title: Text(title),
      ),
      body: Center(
        child: Card(
          child: Column(
            children: [
              Text('Hello'),
              Text('Foo'),
              Semantics(  // workaround
                explicitChildNodes: true,  // workaround
                child: TextField(
                  decoration: InputDecoration(
                    labelText: 'Enter Credit Card',
                    hintText: '1234',
                  ),
                ),
              ),
            ],
          ),
        ),
      ),
    );
  }
}
```

I've found that the workaround doesn't quite suit when there's a sibling text widget for the text field, rather than using the text field's input decoration, as it either doesn't announce the field naturally or doesn't support double tapping to edit the text per the issue description.

With the following example, we get two announcements, which is understandable due to the workaround specifying `explicitChildNodes: true`.  The first is "Favourite planet", then after moving the accessibility focus to the next element we hear "Magarathea, text field, double tap to edit".

```dart
  final controller = TextEditingController(text: 'Magarathea');

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {    
    // This gives two announcements...
    return Column(
      crossAxisAlignment: CrossAxisAlignment.start,
      children: [
        const Text('Favourite planet'),
        Semantics(
          explicitChildNodes: true,
          child: TextField(controller: controller),
        ),
      ],
    );
  }
```

What I want the user to hear is a single announcement "Favourite planet, Magarathea, double tap to edit".

I tried wrapping the column in a `MergeSemantics` widget but that didn't work.  Whilst I got the single announcement that I wanted, double tapping to edit no longer worked.

```dart
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    // This gives a single announcement but double tap to edit doesn't work
    return MergeSemantics(
      child: Column(
        crossAxisAlignment: CrossAxisAlignment.start,
        children: [
          const Text('Favourite planet'),
          Semantics(
            explicitChildNodes: true,
            child: TextField(controller: controller),
          ),
        ],
      ),
    );
  }
```

Instead, I could get what I wanted by excluding the sibling label from semantics and specifying the label on the text field's semantics widget without specifying `explicitChildNodes: true`.

```dart
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    // This gives a single announcement and double tap to edit works
    return Column(
      crossAxisAlignment: CrossAxisAlignment.start,
      children: [
        const ExcludeSemantics(child: Text('Favourite planet')),
        Semantics(
          label: 'Favourite planet',
          child: TextField(controller: controller),
        ),
      ],
    );
  }

```

