Ok, I dug into this further and discovered what's going on. Debugging `text_input.dart`, I found that `_loudlyHandleTextInputInvocation` was not being called under some circumstances. Even when using Flutter's `TextField`, `_loudlyHandleTextInputInvocation` was not being called for the backspace key.

Instead, `EditableText` handles backspace by overriding the `DeleteCharacterIntent`:

https://github.com/flutter/flutter/blob/fbc9f2d5bf6b530d24b7f27c628b2401a23ea630/packages/flutter/lib/src/widgets/editable_text.dart#L5054)

It seems like you can't rely solely on `updateEditingValue` and must also implement a callback for the `DeleteCharacterIntent`. In the OP's example, wrapping the widget with a `FocusableActionDetector` would allow you to handle the backspace key in this scenario:

```dart
@override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return FocusableActionDetector(
      focusNode: widget.focusNode,
      actions: {
        DeleteCharacterIntent: CallbackAction(
          onInvoke: (intent) {
            // This method will be called when backspace is pressed
            print(intent);
          },
        ),
      },
      child: GestureDetector(
        behavior: HitTestBehavior.opaque,
        onTap: _onTap,
        child: ListenableBuilder(
          listenable: widget.controller,
          builder: (context, _) {
            return ConstrainedBox(
              constraints: const BoxConstraints(minWidth: 100, minHeight: 100),
              child: Center(
                child: Text(widget.controller.text),
              ),
            );
          },
        ),
      ),
    );
  }
```

It's a little confusing that backspace is sometimes handled through a `DeleteCharacterIntent` and sometimes through the `MethodChannel` invocation in `text_input.dart`.

I seem to have found the cause of this problem by reading the code in an open source input method project about getting candidate window locations. The location of the candidate window is obtained from the `CursorAnchorInfo`, like this:
```kt
// info is a CursorAnchorInfo
anchorPosition[0] = info.insertionMarkerHorizontal
anchorPosition[1] = info.insertionMarkerBottom
anchorPosition[2] = info.insertionMarkerHorizontal
anchorPosition[3] = info.insertionMarkerTop
```
After I read the source in the flutter engine, in the `shell/platform/android/io/flutter/plugins/editing/InputConnectionAdaptor.java` lines 122, which is a adaptor for android input, I found a way to update the cursor position and it looks like this:
```java
  private CursorAnchorInfo getCursorAnchorInfo() {
    if (mCursorAnchorInfoBuilder == null) {
      mCursorAnchorInfoBuilder = new CursorAnchorInfo.Builder();
    } else {
      mCursorAnchorInfoBuilder.reset();
    }
    mCursorAnchorInfoBuilder.setSelectionRange(
        mEditable.getSelectionStart(), mEditable.getSelectionEnd());
    final int composingStart = mEditable.getComposingStart();
    final int composingEnd = mEditable.getComposingEnd();
    if (composingStart >= 0 && composingEnd > composingStart) {
      mCursorAnchorInfoBuilder.setComposingText(
          composingStart, mEditable.toString().subSequence(composingStart, composingEnd));
    } else {
      mCursorAnchorInfoBuilder.setComposingText(-1, "");
    }
    return mCursorAnchorInfoBuilder.build();
  }
```
In this method of updating the cursor , it seems that the method of updating the cursor position is missing. You can use `mCursorAnchorInfoBuilder.setInsertionMarkerLocation` to update the location, and the way to update the location is as follows, and I am trying to compile the flutter engine myself to verify that this is the cause
```java
    int cursorPosition = mEditable.getSelectionEnd();
    int line = mLayout.getLineForOffset(cursorPosition);
    float horizontalPosition =mLayout.getPrimaryHorizontal(cursorPosition);
    float lineTop = mLayout.getLineTop(line);
    float lineBaseline =mLayout.getLineBaseline(line);
    float lineBottom = mLayout.getLineBottom(line);
    mCursorAnchorInfoBuilder.setInsertionMarkerLocation(horizontalPosition,
            lineTop, lineBaseline, lineBottom, 0);
```

